WEBVTT

00:08.840 --> 00:12.860
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:29.040 --> 00:34.540
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

00:37.280 --> 00:39.040
And here are your hosts.

00:43.760 --> 00:53.080
This is David Crews. And Daryl Lane. If there's such a thing as a science fiction
connoisseur, he would have to be a Jack Vance fan. Vance is a distinctive author

00:53.080 --> 01:01.400
who's been writing science fiction and fantasy since the 1940s. And even in a
field like science fiction, Vance's imagination is remarkable. His depiction of

01:01.400 --> 01:09.320
alien worlds, for instance, impresses any reader. He has a powerful, subtle
style, and with the colors and textures of his descriptions, and his careful

01:09.320 --> 01:16.760
attention to the resources of language, he can make you believe you're on
another planet, somehow involved in an alien culture. We might mention the

01:16.760 --> 01:26.420
Durdane Trilogy or the Four Novels of the Tschai or Planet of Adventure series as
examples of Vance's skill at creating alien environments and cultures. Vance

01:26.420 --> 01:38.860
always wanted to be a writer, and he chose science fiction for the simplest of
reasons. Well, first, I toyed with the idea of my life. And I wanted to find

01:38.860 --> 01:56.080
some way of making a living where I could travel, be my own boss, work my own
hours. And I knew writing was the way that suggested itself. And so I kind of,

01:56.780 --> 02:09.560
even when I was old, maybe 10 or 12 years old, I kind of told myself I kind of
liked to be a writer. Why I chose science fiction, I don't know. Or fantasy,

02:09.640 --> 02:17.480
whatever you want to call it. When I was a kid, I'd done a lot of reading. Well,
I've done a lot of reading and everything, as far as acting.

02:21.380 --> 02:35.980
But I think I'm probably more touched by, or not influenced is the word, but
influenced, I guess you might say, by fantasy

02:35.980 --> 02:48.700
and the so-called science fiction, rather than by much anything else. As we've
said, Vance started back in the 1940s, in the pulp magazines, and his early work

02:48.700 --> 03:00.160
lacks the polish and distinctive flair that he's known for. I was learning my
traits. I just got started writing, not real young, you know, like some guys

03:00.160 --> 03:11.360
did. In fact, I was doing lots of other things. And then I decided I was going
to be a writer, and I started writing. And I had old talibs for it, I guess,

03:11.500 --> 03:25.260
apparently. But I didn't have the knack or the practice, or whatever you want to
call it, of putting the words together. And also, I was trying

03:25.260 --> 03:38.080
to write the wrong kind of story. Those days, the gadget story was very big. And
I wasted a lot of time trying to write gadget stories on scientific

03:38.080 --> 03:56.740
breakthroughs and things like that, which is essentially kind of a lined alley,
I think. And it's a phase of the field which has mercifully gone over the hill.

03:57.540 --> 04:11.020
I've got a very good scientific background. It's not that I don't know science,
I do. I was going to be a physicist, actually, for a while. In the 40s and 50s,

04:11.020 --> 04:27.760
I was writing and experimenting, collecting rejection slips. And that was an
apprentice period in which I

04:27.760 --> 04:39.780
was paid not very much for, but, you know, checked once in a while. But
essentially, those 40 and 50 stories are not much good. They're not worth it.

04:41.880 --> 04:51.380
I'll just soon forget them. Vance's apprenticeship must have been well spent.
The science fiction and fantasy he's been writing ever since is masterful. In

04:51.380 --> 05:01.880
1963, he won the Hugo Award for The Dragon Masters. And in 1966, he won both the
Nebula and Hugo Awards for The Last Castle. Tomorrow, more with Jack Vance.

05:09.640 --> 05:17.660
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

05:17.660 --> 05:18.440
Odessa, Texas.

