Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:19.360 --> 06:24.620
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

06:27.440 --> 06:29.040
And here are your hosts.

06:33.860 --> 06:42.980
This is Daryl Lane. And David Crews. Jack Vance has created a unique, vivid, and
fascinating body of science fiction and fantasy. He began his career in the pulp

06:42.980 --> 06:50.740
magazines of the 1940s, and he wrote the gadget stories that were popular then.
But over the years, he's developed a deeper, more subtle, and distinctive type

06:50.740 --> 06:58.720
of science fiction and fantasy. Yet the curious fact is that not many people,
even science fiction readers, have heard of Jack Vance. We asked him why he

06:58.720 --> 07:14.740
thought that was so. I think another thing, too, that I've developed rather
gradually and reached my presence, whatever you want to call it, by a kind of

07:14.740 --> 07:30.520
back way, inconspicuously. I've never... Clark is known for 2001. Heinlein,
Stranger in a Strange Land, or whatever, children's books, or through Campbell.

07:35.260 --> 07:53.560
And it's... It's... I've never been associated with anything that had any other
publicity attached to it. So I just seem to arrive on the scene. And so it seems

07:53.560 --> 08:06.280
to me, if I were looking at my own career in this way, kind of quietly from...
from... from... northeast somewhere. Rather than... through... through having...

08:06.280 --> 08:18.320
a... a movie or... or something or something. Lately, Vance has been writing
three, four, and even five novel series set on alien planets. He's noted for his

08:18.320 --> 08:26.180
imaginative descriptions of alien settings and cultures more than anything else.
The four books in the Chai series, or the Dordain trilogy, are good examples of

08:26.180 --> 08:34.540
stories set in convincingly alien environments. Vance is also recognized for the
stories in the Dying Earth series. And don't forget, Vance has written excellent

08:34.540 --> 08:43.840
mystery fiction, even winning the Edgar Award from the Mystery Writers of
America in 1960 for his book The Man in the Cage. Even though some readers talk

08:43.840 --> 08:54.260
of a unique Vance style, Vance himself says he has no particular style or
writing characteristics. I don't have any style. All I do is try to write

08:54.260 --> 09:07.440
whatever in the best possible way. Now, if you take the trouble to read some of
my murder mysteries, you'll find that they're written in a different way.

09:08.620 --> 09:20.840
Everything you write, everything I write, everything anybody writes, the style
or the way the words are put together is part of the mood of the story. It is

09:20.840 --> 09:35.700
part of the story itself. It's part of the completed product. Now, when you say,
how did I evolve this, that implies that I have one style that I use for

09:35.700 --> 09:54.900
everything from this early Dying Earth thing up to one of this mystery story
with Locallum in the countryside out here called Fox Valley Murders. If you take

09:54.900 --> 10:04.100
the trouble to examine the way the words are put together, you'll find it
totally different. Also, like in Bad Ronald, which is a suspense story, the way

10:04.100 --> 10:13.300
that the words go together are different from the way the words go together. You
say, oh, I don't know what. No, I don't have any style.

10:21.080 --> 10:30.540
Vance considers himself a storyteller or entertainer with no axes to grind. He's
reluctant to provide explanations or analyses of his work. When asked about a

10:30.540 --> 10:40.400
particular character or episode in one of his works, Vance has a characteristic
reply. Well, I think everybody will have to answer that for themselves. Reading

10:40.400 --> 10:46.480
the science fiction of Jack Vance makes answering questions like that
worthwhile. More with Jack Vance tomorrow.

