12:12.340 --> 12:13.940
And here are your hosts.

12:18.500 --> 12:27.760
This is David Crews. And Daryl Lane. The dying Earth stories of Jack Vance, one
of the most exquisite creations in the realm of science fantasy. The setting for

12:27.760 --> 12:36.540
the stories is a bit unusual. It's Earth, but an Earth so many millions of
centuries into the future that it's almost dead. And so is the sun, sputtering

12:36.540 --> 12:44.640
like a candle ready to go out and bathing Earth in its final pale red light.
There are only a few people left on Earth, and most of these are sorcerers,

12:44.780 --> 12:54.520
since magic works and science has been forgotten. Vance says that the dying
Earth stories are some of the earliest things he ever wrote. Well, the funny

12:54.520 --> 13:06.920
thing about it is that was written before I'd started selling. That was written
at sea, as well as merchant sea. And I had quite a bit of a spare time, and I

13:06.920 --> 13:13.420
began writing these flamboyant,

13:13.500 --> 13:30.160
highly colored stories. But those were written, oh, very, very early. They were
written before I'd even started selling. So they're just representative of a

13:30.160 --> 13:34.080
kind of rather early stage.

13:35.400 --> 13:47.860
And then when I started writing this so-called gadget fiction or other stuff, I
changed the style. The style of this dying Earth stuff wasn't at all suitable

13:47.860 --> 14:00.520
for writing the stuff I began selling. The stuff I was selling was any good,
because it wasn't. But at least the style of the dying Earth would have been

14:00.520 --> 14:05.840
absolutely, what's

14:05.840 --> 14:10.280
the word, incongruous. It wouldn't have fitted, so I used a different style.

14:22.260 --> 14:30.080
Many readers believe the style of the stories, which Vance calls flamboyant and
highly colored, to be the most marvelous and vivid thing about them. It creates

14:30.080 --> 14:38.020
an exotic yet wistful atmosphere, somehow appropriate for a world on the edge of
extinction. Tim Underwood is a friend of Vance's, and along with Chuck Miller,

14:38.280 --> 14:46.020
publishes Vance's work in specially made collector's editions. The Underwood
-Miller Publishing Company's first book was The Dying Earth. We asked Tim

14:46.020 --> 15:00.820
Underwood why. A lot of science fiction and fantasy, and sometimes the best of
it, does not get published in hardcover editions. And The Dying Earth was the

15:00.820 --> 15:14.860
first book we did, and it was just a book that is essentially a classic. It was
published in 1950 as a paperback, and it had never been in hardcover. And it's

15:14.860 --> 15:23.900
just one of the outstanding books in the fantasy field, and 200 years from now
people will be reading it. And it had never been in a durable hardcover edition,

15:23.960 --> 15:25.140
and so we put it in one.

15:32.740 --> 15:41.420
Vance didn't write any new Dying Earth material for 15 years after the book's
original publication in 1950. We asked him if it was perhaps reader responses,

15:41.440 --> 15:56.680
which caused him to take it up again. No, it's been, I don't, I just always
wanted to do some more stuff in there. Uh, and this character was, uh, swarming

15:56.680 --> 15:57.500
around in my head.

16:14.780 --> 16:22.780
The character swarming around in his head was Kugel, a picaresque rogue who
survived on the dying earth through his wits and his nimble fingers. The Kugel

16:22.780 --> 16:31.440
stories were collected in 1966 in a book entitled The Eyes of the Overworld.
Since then, Vance has written other Kugel stories and says he'll do more in the

16:31.440 --> 16:35.940
future, so the dying earth isn't dead yet. More on Jack Vance tomorrow.

