18:06.160 --> 18:14.640
This is Daryl Lane. And David Crews. Jack Vance is one of the major talents that
the field of fantasy and science fiction has produced. Tim Underwood, his friend

18:14.640 --> 18:25.900
and publisher, offers some reasons why. I think Jack has accomplished some
things with some of his works that have just never been done before. Not only in

18:25.900 --> 18:41.860
terms of style, but in terms of feeling. And he hearkens to a certain spirit, I
think. I mean, a certain kind of person or a certain kind of spirit is on his

18:41.860 --> 18:55.420
wavelength and responds strongly to his work. But the latter part of his work
and the best of his work is extremely well crafted. He's a craftsman, very well

18:55.420 --> 19:05.940
written, and accomplishes a lot of really unusual things in a very quiet way.
Vance's accomplishments have been impressive. His science fiction career spans

19:05.940 --> 19:13.980
almost 40 years and began back in the pulp era. He's won the major awards for a
science fiction and fantasy writer. One is the Hugo Award, awarded by readers,

19:14.220 --> 19:22.180
and the other is a Nebula Award, given by other writers. Some of his best-known
work includes the Dying Earth stories, which go all the way back to his

19:22.180 --> 19:31.140
beginnings as a writer in the 40s, and more recently the five Demon Princes
novels. Still, Vance hasn't received much recognition. We asked Underwood why.

19:32.420 --> 19:37.580
My feeling is that one

19:37.580 --> 19:52.040
responds strongly to Vance, one who feels much the same way about the world that
he does. And I think, why isn't he, though, as popular as, say, John Lycoray,

19:52.320 --> 20:00.240
who I think people respond to in the same way? Well, Vance is more of a rarefied
taste, I think.

20:03.160 --> 20:14.340
He's the kind of things that he feels are important. The strangeness in the
world about us and the unusual qualities of life itself, those kind of

20:14.340 --> 20:25.940
considerations are not important to a lot of people. People who do feel these
things strongly are going to like what Vance writes. They're going to enjoy

20:25.940 --> 20:34.800
reading. They're going to enjoy the worlds that he's created. He's not done a
lot of the things that make other writers successful, like he's never stayed

20:34.800 --> 20:52.520
with one character, the way, let's say, Le Carré stayed with Smiley. Or the way
that someone writes a Doc Savage novel 15 times in a row or whatever. He hasn't

20:52.520 --> 21:09.520
done that. And he hasn't had one hero that he's repeated for any great number of
books. And he hasn't had one contemporary theme that appeals to people, like the

21:09.520 --> 21:24.960
battle of the sexes or something like that. Those aren't Jack's themes. Jack's
consideration themes are enormously subtle and kind of a rarefied nature. Vance

21:24.960 --> 21:34.120
has always been reluctant to discuss his own work or to offer any insights into
his themes or intentions. Underwood suggests a reason. Jack always says that he

21:34.120 --> 21:46.640
wants his work to stand for and by itself. I think he just wants to be
remembered for his work. He refuses to pick favorites among his work. I know he

21:46.640 --> 22:01.280
likes his Demon Prince series a lot for good reason. He likes The Palace of
Love, which is the third in that series. He likes The Eyes of the Overworld, the

22:01.280 --> 22:16.020
sequenced stories of the fellow Kugel. And that's partly because Kugel's a
rascal. And Vance himself is a bit of a rascal. And Kugel's even more so. He's

22:16.020 --> 22:22.440
the kind of rascal that Vance would like to be if he wasn't such a nice guy at
heart.

