23:52.480 --> 24:01.580
This is David Crews. And Daryl Lane. In 1975, a science fiction and fantasy
publishing company was formed because two men wanted to get one particular

24:01.580 --> 24:15.560
science fantasy book between hardcovers. Tim Underwood, one of the men,
explains. In 1975, I decided I wanted to publish a book. Specifically, I wanted

24:15.560 --> 24:27.860
to publish The Dying Earth in a hardcover form. And I was a used book dealer,
and Chuck Miller was a used book dealer, dealing in rare and out-of-print books

24:27.860 --> 24:41.420
and some new material. And we knew of each other. And I think we had bought and
sold books from each other from time to time. And Chuck heard about, I may have

24:41.420 --> 24:51.640
mentioned in a letter about The Dying Earth. And Chuck offered his expertise
because he knew a good deal about certain parts of publishing industry, about

24:51.640 --> 25:05.500
distribution and that end of it. And my experience, my limited experience, had
to do with just graphically putting a book together. And so he suggested that we

25:05.500 --> 25:16.320
do the book together. And so we did. And the interesting thing is that we never
met each other until the book had already been published. And that was a year

25:16.320 --> 25:17.800
later in 1976.

25:20.300 --> 25:32.340
And up to that time, we were literally exchanging thousands of dollars through
the mail and doing business without ever having met each other. We were, in a

25:32.340 --> 25:42.300
sense, complete strangers. But we had this one connection, and that is we both
felt strongly about this one work of Vance's The Dying Earth and about Vance's

25:42.300 --> 25:52.640
work in general and specifically about fantasy and science fiction and horror
and literature. Since that first book, the Underwood Miller Company has

25:52.640 --> 26:01.380
published some 50 books, all science fiction, fantasy, and horror. Their print
runs for each volume average 1,000 copies, hardly enough to compete with the

26:01.380 --> 26:11.840
large New York publishers. Underwood explains why. We're selling to collectors,
and the collectors are buying these books with the knowledge that they're going

26:11.840 --> 26:28.340
to go out of print and become valuable later on. Another reason is that Chuck
and I don't own a warehouse, and we are not in business to have a large

26:28.340 --> 26:39.220
inventory. We would make more money if we printed more books, because as you
print more books, the cost per book of manufacturing goes down dramatically.

26:42.720 --> 26:52.640
But we just simply can't afford to have a lot of books in inventory sitting
around. We can't afford... Our books go out of print in about nine months, and

26:52.640 --> 27:03.200
this is just the opposite of a major manufacturer, like Dutton or Brown or
someone like that. They want their book to stay in print as long as possible,

27:03.360 --> 27:06.820
and we want our books to go out of print as soon as possible.

27:14.580 --> 27:23.420
Tim Underwood and Chuck Miller have a sincere interest in significant works of
science fiction and fantasy. It's not just the pleasure of bookmaking. Just the

27:23.420 --> 27:35.220
pleasure. Chuck and I both take a great pleasure in making a good book, a book
that has its signature sewn, which is something that doesn't occur in general

27:35.220 --> 27:46.660
trade hardcover publishing anymore, a book that's printed on acid-free paper so
that in 20 or 30 years the paper won't turn brittle and brown, and just a well

27:46.660 --> 27:57.000
-made, well-bound book, attractively made and artistically put together. And
publishing a book like that, creating a book like that, is really a pleasure.

27:58.360 --> 28:05.440
Underwood and Miller are publishing books by many authors in beautifully
illustrated editions now. Anyone who likes fantasy and science fiction, and

28:05.440 --> 28:09.000
anyone who likes books, should search out some of their work and hold on to it.

